==English==
{{wikipedia|sovereignty}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|soverain|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|VL.}} root *''superānus'' (cf. Italian ''[[sovrano]]'', Spanish ''[[soberano]]'') from Latin {{term|super||above|lang=la}} and the Latinate English suffix {{term|-ity|-ty|lang=eng}}. Spelling influenced by folk-etymology association with reign.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈsɒv.ɹən.ti/|/ˈsɒv.ɹɪn.ti}}, {{SAMPA|/"sQv.r\@n.ti/|/"sQv.rIn.ti/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|sovereignties|-}}

# {{context|of a nation}} The state of making laws and controlling resources without the coercion of other nations.
# {{context|of a ruler}} Supreme authority over all things. (as in an emperor, king, dictator, or God, ref. ‘King of kings, and Lord of lords’)
# {{context|of self}} The liberty to decide one's thoughts and actions.

